Quality:
We would control for Quality by making surveys and distributing them to visitors of the Technology Garden. Ideally, we would like to have the visitors take the survey before and after we had improved the garden, with a sample size that is large enough. Doing this will ensure that current problems will be fixed to the best of our abilities and that any of the underlying issues afterwards can be reviewed and improved on. This will also allow us to decide whether or not there was a statistically significant improvement in satisfaction with the garden. Only then we can consider that our project is complete.

Another way of improving quality is by interviewing the teachers and staff of that floor who interact with the garden and make sure that they are satisfied too. Like with the first survey, we would use the Likert scores (1-5) in determining this. 
We would also ask the original Technology Garden staff to make sure that at least some of them approved of our project and its results, which would show that it had succeeded. 

Besides this, we would also take metrics of the website and count the amount of hits to track who uses it and to make sure that it is actually being used.

Risks:
Sensors not Connecting to Site: We have several site options in mind, and some backup sensor plans should things go pear-shaped.
Website design not working with visitors: We can interview some users and help design a new design. Our site design is flexible enough to allow a new UI to be swapped in at any time.
Website server issues: We will have a backup copy so that we can swap to a different server if need be.
Damage to Sensors: Our choice to build our own sensors has allowed us to make extra in case of this event.
Website is damaged: Backups will handle this.
Our sensors work by measuring the variable resistance of the soil that they are in and because of this, it will be hard to hold all measurements recorded to the same moisture benchmark. This is because different types of soil are more conductive than others. In researching this problem there were a few proposed fixes to this issue. 
Inserting the probes (nails) into Plaster of Paris a fixed distance apart to allow the sensors to measure the moisture of the plaster instead of the soil. 
Use the plaster technique above but surround the sensor with sand to wick away the moisture allowing the plaster to dry more efficiently.
Attaching a non-conductive material such a plastic between the two probes A fixed distance apart.
